{"reasoning":"The bug is a classic lost-update race caused by splitting increment into separate read and write steps without mutual exclusion or versioning. Under interleaving, both increment operations capture the same old value and then both write back old+1, so one increment is overwritten. To make the counter correct under any interleaving in this step-based simulation, each increment must be performed as an atomic read-modify-write from the perspective of interleaving. Since the file is a simulation using step functions, the simplest safe fix is to collapse increment into a single step that reads the current counter and writes back current+1 before any other increment can interleave. The sequential and interleaved demo helpers can continue to work, but the increment itself must no longer expose a vulnerable read/write split.","files":{"code_snippets_v2/lost_update/counter.py":""""Counter with non-atomic read-modify-write, simulated via step functions."""

